21. What is DML?
Definition

DML (Data Manipulation Language) is a category of SQL commands used to insert, update, delete, and retrieve data from database tables.

Unlike DDL, DML works with the data inside tables, not the table structure.

Common DML Commands
INSERT
UPDATE
DELETE
SELECT (often classified as DQL, but sometimes grouped with DML in learning materials)
Syntax
INSERT INTO table_name (...);
UPDATE table_name SET ...;
DELETE FROM table_name;
SELECT * FROM table_name;
Example
CREATE TABLE Students(
    StudentID INT,
    Name VARCHAR(50),
    Age INT
);

INSERT INTO Students
VALUES(101,'Rahul',20);
22. INSERT Statement
Definition

The INSERT statement is used to add one or more new records into a table.

Syntax
Insert all values
INSERT INTO table_name
VALUES(value1, value2, value3);
Insert selected columns
INSERT INTO table_name(column1, column2)
VALUES(value1, value2);
Example
INSERT INTO Students
VALUES(101,'Rahul',20);

Table

StudentID	Name	Age
101	Rahul	20

Insert another row

INSERT INTO Students
VALUES(102,'Priya',21);
23. UPDATE Statement
Definition

The UPDATE statement is used to modify existing records in a table.

Usually used with a WHERE clause to update specific rows.

Syntax
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = value
WHERE condition;
Example

Before

ID	Name	Age
101	Rahul	20
UPDATE Students
SET Age = 21
WHERE StudentID = 101;

After

ID	Name	Age
101	Rahul	21
24. DELETE Statement
Definition

The DELETE statement removes one or more rows from a table.

The table structure remains unchanged.

Syntax

Delete specific rows

DELETE FROM table_name
WHERE condition;

Delete all rows

DELETE FROM table_name;
Example

Before

ID	Name
101	Rahul
102	Priya
DELETE FROM Students
WHERE StudentID = 102;

After

ID	Name
101	Rahul
25. Difference Between DELETE and TRUNCATE
DELETE	TRUNCATE
DML Command	DDL Command
Deletes selected or all rows	Deletes all rows only
Uses WHERE clause	Cannot use WHERE
Can be rolled back (before commit)	Usually cannot be rolled back after execution (DBMS-dependent)
Slower	Faster
Table structure remains	Table structure remains
Identity values usually continue	Identity values are often reset (DBMS-dependent)
Example
DELETE
DELETE FROM Students
WHERE StudentID = 101;

Deletes only Student 101.

TRUNCATE
TRUNCATE TABLE Students;

Deletes all rows from the table.

26. WHERE Clause
Definition

The WHERE clause is used to filter records based on a specified condition.

Without WHERE, SQL affects all rows.

Syntax
SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE condition;
Example
SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Age > 20;

Table

ID	Name	Age
101	Rahul	20
102	Priya	22
103	Aman	19

Output

ID	Name	Age
102	Priya	22
27. LIMIT / TOP
Definition

LIMIT (used in MySQL and PostgreSQL) and TOP (used in SQL Server) are used to restrict the number of rows returned by a query.

Syntax
MySQL
SELECT *
FROM table_name
LIMIT number;
SQL Server
SELECT TOP number *
FROM table_name;
Example
MySQL
SELECT *
FROM Students
LIMIT 3;

Returns the first 3 rows.

SQL Server
SELECT TOP 3 *
FROM Students;

Also returns the first 3 rows.

28. ORDER BY
Definition

The ORDER BY clause is used to sort query results in ascending or descending order.

ASC → Ascending (default)
DESC → Descending
Syntax

Ascending

SELECT *
FROM table_name
ORDER BY column_name ASC;

Descending

SELECT *
FROM table_name
ORDER BY column_name DESC;
Example

Table

Name	Salary
Rahul	40000
Priya	55000
Aman	45000
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Salary DESC;

Output

Name	Salary
Priya	55000
Aman	45000
Rahul	40000
29. DISTINCT
Definition

The DISTINCT keyword removes duplicate values and returns only unique records.

Syntax
SELECT DISTINCT column_name
FROM table_name;
Example

Table

Department
HR
IT
HR
Sales
IT
SELECT DISTINCT Department
FROM Employee;

Output

Department
HR
IT
Sales

Duplicate values are removed.

30. Handling NULL Values
Definition

NULL represents a missing or unknown value.

To check for NULL, use:

IS NULL
IS NOT NULL

You cannot use = or != with NULL.

Syntax

Find NULL values

SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NULL;

Find non-NULL values

SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name IS NOT NULL;
Example

Table

ID	Name	Phone
1	Rahul	9876543210
2	Priya	NULL
3	Aman	9999999999

Find students with no phone number

SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Phone IS NULL;

Output

ID	Name	Phone
2	Priya	NULL

Find students with phone numbers

SELECT *
FROM Students
WHERE Phone IS NOT NULL;

Output

ID	Name	Phone
1	Rahul	9876543210
3	Aman	9999999999
